                  <bindingDesc>
                     <binding notBefore="1775" notAfter="1838">
                        <p>Probably bound in the <placeName cert="high"
                              ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208" key="place_7000208"
                              >Indian subcontinent</placeName>.</p>
                        <p>Sewn at two stations, unsupported. Edges trimmed, and chevron endbands of
                           pale pink and natural colour twined at <locus from="Head" to="Head"
                              >head</locus> and <locus from="Tail" to="Tail">tail</locus>. Covered
                           in full red-brown goatskin <material>leather</material> over
                              <material>pastebaords</material>. The interior lined with doublures of
                           the same leather, with their excess widths adhered to the first and last
                           flyleaves as hinges connecting the cover to the textblock, with vertical
                           strips of paper applied over tip to disguise the joins. </p>
                        <decoNote type="binding">Small typed naskh spine label bears the
                           title.</decoNote>
                        <p><dimensions type="binding" unit="mm">
                              <height>212</height>
                              <width>142</width>
                              <depth>54</depth>
                           </dimensions></p>
                        <condition>Handle binding with caution. In fair but stable condition with
                           extensive abrasion to the exterior, head and tail caps torn, and
                           protruding textblock.</condition>
                     </binding>
                  </bindingDesc>
               </physDesc>

               <history>
                  <origin>Probably completed in the <origPlace cert="high"
                        ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208" key="place_7000208">Indian
                        subcontinent</origPlace>; undated but probably <date cert="high"
                        calendar="#Gregorian" notBefore="1760" notAfter="1837">late 18th
                        century.</date></origin>
                  <provenance><p>Subsequently acqurired by one <q xml:lang="en">Col MacKay</q> who
                        signed the paper label on the <locus from="Upper_front_cover"
                           to="Upper_front_cover">right board exterior</locus> and the <locus
                           from="ia" to="ia">right flyleaf a side</locus>. He may possibly be
                           <persName cert="medium" role="ins fmo ato" key="person_f8555">James
                           MacKay (d. 1831)</persName> who served in the British East Indian Company
                        and who previously owned another manuscript now held in the Cambridge
                        University Library (<ref
                           target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_356">Add.
                        796</ref>).</p></provenance>
                  <provenance>
                     <p>While the circumstances under which this volume arrived in Britain remain
                        unclear, orientalist <persName type="standard"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/66617580/" key="person_66617580" role="fmo"
                           change="#role-assignment">Duncan Forbes (1798–1868)</persName> later
                        obtained it from an unidentified source. Ultimately appointed
                           <orgName>King's College</orgName> Professor of Oriental Languages, Forbes
                        described this volume in his <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1866"
                           >1866</date> catalogue, valued at £1 11<hi rend="italic">s</hi> 6<hi
                           rend="italic">d</hi> (also inscribed on the <locus from="ib" to="ib"
                           >first right flyleaf b side (f. ib)</locus>), before he sold his
                        manuscript collection to his publisher <orgName role="bsl"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/152259747" key="person_152259747"><persName
                              key="person_45159035185601380002" role="bsl" change="#prov-markup">W.
                              H. Allen </persName>&amp; Co.</orgName> in exchange for an
                        annuity.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance>
                     <p>Subsequently sold by <orgName role="bsl"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/152259747" key="person_152259747"><persName
                              key="person_45159035185601380002" role="bsl" change="#prov-markup">W.
                              H. Allen </persName>&amp; Co.</orgName> to <persName type="standard"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/97751058/" key="person_97751058" role="fmo"
                           change="#role-assignment">Alexander Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford
                           (1812–1880)</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1866"
                           >1866</date> for his Bibliotheca Lindesiana at Haigh Hall, <placeName
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7010384" key="place_7010384"
                           >Wigan</placeName>.</p>
                  </provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Purchased by <persName role="dnr" key="person_f6379"
                           change="#prov-markup">Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date
                           calendar="#Gregorian" when="1901">1901</date> from <persName role="fmo"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/9985420/" key="person_9985420">James Ludovic
                           Lindsay, 26th Earl of Crawford (1847–1913)</persName>.</p></provenance>
                  <acquisition>
                     <p>Bequeathed by <persName key="person_f6379" change="#prov-markup">Enriqueta
                           Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1908"
                           >1908</date> to the <orgName type="corporation" role="rps"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/312795145/">John Rylands Library</orgName>,
                           <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7010477"
                           key="place_7010477">Manchester</placeName>.</p>
                  </acquisition>
               </history>
